items.poem_body:
Morning folds light into the cup of my hands;  
a sparrow startles the silence into song.  
For one bright breath, the whole world feels small enough to love.

Beneath a streetlamp’s amber flame,  
the evening gathers, soft and tame;  
a sparrow stitches dusk to air,  
and every passing footstep’s prayer.  

I carry quiet in my sleeves,  
old stories, warm as worn-out leaves;  
the night unfolds, a borrowed book—  
turning its pages by each look.  

So let the worries grow no crown;  
let starlight find what you’ve let down;  
if tomorrow knocks, I’ll sing—  
small hope, in a human thing.

Moonlight folds the night in silver thread,  
A hush of stars blooms softly overhead;  
One breath of wind, and all the dark takes flight.
